<div id="review_48460343" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/48460343" />
    <a title="Proctodeal Trophallaxus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2102585-proctodeal-trophallaxus"><img alt="Proctodeal Trophallaxus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1236379053p2/2102585.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/48460343?book_show_action=true">Mar 06, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Proctodeal Trophallaxus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Proctodeal Trophallaxus" href="/user/show/2102585-proctodeal-trophallaxus">Proctodeal Trophallaxus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780374505240" href="/book/show/48468.The_Violent_Bear_It_Away">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer48460343" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1528385879647156669">I read this book after finishing her <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18490.Frankenstein' title='Frankenstein by Mary Shelley' rel='nofollow noopener'>collected short stories</a> and Wise Blood, her first novel. None of her other work prepared me for this, her cynical, paranoid mind fuck of a novel. Her prose, as always, is clear and excellent, and she once again explores faith and its absence in a way that allows for no easy solutions, no pat answers. But Christ on a crutch is this a difficult book. One of the things I love about her work is the wry sense of humor laced through it, balancing out the dark theme</span>
  <span id="freeText1528385879647156669" style="display:none">I read this book after finishing her <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18490.Frankenstein" title="Frankenstein by Mary Shelley" rel="nofollow noopener">collected short stories</a> and Wise Blood, her first novel. None of her other work prepared me for this, her cynical, paranoid mind fuck of a novel. Her prose, as always, is clear and excellent, and she once again explores faith and its absence in a way that allows for no easy solutions, no pat answers. But Christ on a crutch is this a difficult book. One of the things I love about her work is the wry sense of humor laced through it, balancing out the dark themes and bursts of violence. That humor is unfortunately missing from 'Violent', making for a grim read about two wholly unlikeable characters who spend most of the book in a power struggle over the soul of a young mentally challenged boy. While there are some wonderful moments -O'Connor once again proves that she is the master of the 'telling detail'- all in all I found this a troubling, exhausting read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1528385879647156669" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


