    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_116764736" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/116764736" />
    <a title="Skylar Burris" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/710201-skylar-burris"><img alt="Skylar Burris" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1449959508p2/710201.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/116764736?book_show_action=true">Aug 14, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Skylar Burris" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Skylar Burris" href="/user/show/710201-skylar-burris">Skylar Burris</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780374505240" href="/book/show/48468.The_Violent_Bear_It_Away">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer116764736" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14571495950183860253">I was struck by this book, but I feel I have not yet understood it. As I read this, I kept thinking of O&apos;Connor&apos;s remark in an interview that the south, if not exactly Christ-centered, is &quot;Christ haunted.&quot; This is a disturbing, difficult book, and I was left wondering, &quot;What does it all mean?&quot; O’Connor reminds me of another Catholic author, Graham Greene, in her depiction of the Christian religious person as sinful, dark, violent, passionate, vibrantly alive, touched and consumed and overpowered</span>
  <span id="freeText14571495950183860253" style="display:none">I was struck by this book, but I feel I have not yet understood it. As I read this, I kept thinking of O'Connor's remark in an interview that the south, if not exactly Christ-centered, is "Christ haunted." This is a disturbing, difficult book, and I was left wondering, "What does it all mean?" O’Connor reminds me of another Catholic author, Graham Greene, in her depiction of the Christian religious person as sinful, dark, violent, passionate, vibrantly alive, touched and consumed and overpowered at moments by the power of God or of grace, as juxtaposed with the secular (or the bourgeois or the new age) person who is blandly respectable, does no great evil (or great good), is wishy-washy, lukewarm, void of meaningful emotional depths. This contrast is so stark in the writing of both authors that it makes the religious Christian figures (as awful as they are) appear amazingly substantive against the insubstantial shells that are the non-religious characters. It is a way of powerfully depicting the substance of the spiritual realm, a reality that is more real than real, that is so real that it makes everything that does not allow itself to be touched by it seem hollow. I don't know how I feel about this take on Christianity. I see some truth in it ("Be ye either hot or cold or I will spew you out of my mouth"), but at the same time it is disturbing, and it leaves no room for a quiet, joyful, commonplace Christianity. When I read these types of books, I am struck for days with a kind of image of them, with an emotional imprint, and at the same time I do not like them. I do not like them and yet they feel strangely real, strangely true, in a sense I can't quite penatrate with mere reason. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14571495950183860253" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


