  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1448886750" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1448886750" />
    <a title="Tom LA" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4252261-tom-la"><img alt="Tom LA" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578866627p2/4252261.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1448886750?book_show_action=true">Nov 21, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom LA" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom LA" href="/user/show/4252261-tom-la">Tom LA</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780374505240" href="/book/show/48468.The_Violent_Bear_It_Away">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1448886750&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1448886750" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15781829815624721138">&quot;The violent bear it away&quot;, a novel that&apos;s been categorized as &quot;Southern Gothic&quot;, is written with elegance and with an intensity verging on anger. You know that buzzing noise you hear when walking below those overhead high-voltage power lines? And the buzzing feels like it&apos;s getting to your skin? This novel is like that (like everything I&apos;ve read of O&apos;Connor so far): charged up with a LOT of electricity. <br/><br/>It&apos;s an allegorical tale, every character a symbol or a metaphor for something clearly defin</span>
  <span id="freeText15781829815624721138" style="display:none">"The violent bear it away", a novel that's been categorized as "Southern Gothic", is written with elegance and with an intensity verging on anger. You know that buzzing noise you hear when walking below those overhead high-voltage power lines? And the buzzing feels like it's getting to your skin? This novel is like that (like everything I've read of O'Connor so far): charged up with a LOT of electricity. <br /><br />It's an allegorical tale, every character a symbol or a metaphor for something clearly defined: religious zeal, modern rationalism, and the modern man of the '50s, who is struggling between the two, while walking in a very dark world. <br /><br />At times, it gave me a very "Catcher in the Rye" feeling, of course the Southern Gothic version of it, but that same visceral pull, a kind of deep, raw fascination conveyed by the intensity and the conflicted confusion of adolescence. <br /><br />But it just doesn't work. Both as a parable and as a story, I found this novel to be a bloody mess.<br /><br />The first part was originally a short story, and I would have preferred it that way. I loved the crazy back and forth dialogue between the stocky great uncle and young Tarwater. The scene where the uncle is laying in his own coffin, with only his protruding belly popping out, barking orders at his nephew about the details of his burial, is a fantastic little surreal piece.<br /><br />Unfortunately, somehow this work became a novel where, as odd as it sounds, the mentally ill have the responsibility to defend the validity of the Christian faith. <br /><br />The story presents a cast of charachters who go from abusive to dangerously sociopathic. Of course, they cause themselves and each other a lot of harm. O'Connor used to go church every day, and she used her writing to preach. Towards the end of this novel, she wants the reader to forget about her characters' mental illness, and even to forget that one of them is an unconvicted murderer. <br /><br />That is what doesn't work. Allegories are better placed in religious texts - and there are already more than enough. To the reader in search for a good novel, these characters who represent ideas become dull very soon. Everything happens in this kind of magic-realism haze, but if you don't know that you should take the characters as symbols, you end up very confused. <br /><br />What you are supposed to do is swallow the whole thing as a parable, the weirdest and darkest parable you've ever heard. <br /><br />O'Connor has an endless reservoir of anger for secular modernity, psychology and rationalism. All these find their incarnation in the character of the School Teacher, against whom she unleashes her own personal fury: the poor guy is constantly irritated, furious, angry and lives a life of pain because he doesn't allow himself to love. <br /><br />The equation secularity/rationalism = refusal to love is never articulated, and I find it very weak. <br /><br />In any case, there you go: if you don't follow O'Connor orthodox, rigid and quite angry type of catholic faith, you are unable to love. Wow. What a disappointingly narrow-minded view of non-christian people. <br /><br />Let's hear it from the author herself, from an interview: "Writers who see by the light of their Christian faith will have, in these times, the sharpest eye for the grotesque, for the perverse, and for the unacceptable…. To the hard of hearing you shout, and for the almost-blind you draw large and startling figures".<br /><br />How sad and delusional is that? Did she seriously mean to evangelize to the blind and deaf non-believers with this disturbing, obscure oddness of a book?<br /><br />Her "large and startling figures" had the complete opposite effect on me: I didn't take anything of what they were saying seriously, because they were total nutters. Only towards the end you realize that O'Connor was actually siding with the great uncle-nutcase all along. Yes, the great man who messed up the lives of two nephews with his insanity, and even attempted to murder one of them. To me, that just doesn't work.<br /><br />So I did some research, and I was glad to discover that O'Connor HERSELF was unconvinced about this novel, even after she had finished it. (I really should have read her short stories instead). <br /><br />This is from Paul Elie’s book, "An American Pilgrimage", describing Flannery’s struggle to write and to finish this book:<br /><br />“She was calling it The Violent Bear It Away, and the title suggested the struggle of writing it. She saw it as a book about baptism, and thought the challenge was to get the reader to see baptism as a matter of life and death. She had to “bend the whole novel” so that the baptism carried “enough awe and mystery to jar the reader into some kind of emotional recognition of its significance.<br /><br />“So she bent the novel toward what she supposed were the modern reader’s sympathies. It would be a novel of initiation, about the boy’s entry into manhood, a motif the reader would recognize. It would begin and end with a religious ritual: in the beginning the ritual of death, the boy’s burial of his great uncle, who is a prophet, and in the end the ritual of life, the baptism of his nephew, who is mentally challenged. It would lead the reader to see these rituals in the way that she saw them herself – baptism as the initiation into the life of grace, and burial as the initiation into the life of eternity.<br /><br />“Thus described, her approach has a Jamesian elegance, but in practice it proved so unwieldy that simply keeping the story straight became her biggest challenge. <br /><br />“She finished in January 1959, nearly seven years after she started. “I am more and more satisfied with the title and less and less satisfied with the rest of it", she told Hester. To the Fitzgeralds she wrote, “I cannot see it any longer and the only thing I can determine about it is that nobody else would have wanted to write it but me."<br /><br />She could not see it any longer, and I certainly cannot see it today in 2015! <br /><br />There is an incredible talent in her writing though. Let's go grab her short stories.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15781829815624721138" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


